occurrences.line_text: On hideous strokes with most importune might,
Their cruell strokes and terrible affright;
And heaped strokes did round about him haile
And round about with boystrous strokes oppresse,
Who when he once his dreadfull strokes had tasted,
With such huge strokes, approued oft in fight,
When all his strokes he saw auoyded quite,
They fall to strokes, the frute of too much talke:
Whenas no strength, nor stroks mote him constraine
To stay her stroks, and he himselfe would yield:
Vnto the other side of that wide strond,
But marched to the strond, their passage to require.
Backe to the strond retyrd, and there still stayd,
Foreby that idle strond, of him were told,
Which long hath waited by the Stygian strond.
Is throwne on the Rich strond:
Along the strond, which as she ouer-went,
Rich strond to trauell, whereas he did wonne,
Who through late triall, on that wealthy Strond
Of the Rich strond, their charets they forlore,
Fled fearefull Daphne on th'ï¿½gï¿½an strond,
It will be at the Castle of the strond;
Departed from the Castle of the strond,
And proou'd your strength on a strong enimie,
Ye all forwearied be: for what so strong,
O how can beautie maister the most strong,
But with her went along, as a strong gard
Where Archimago said a felon strong
For he was strong, and of so mightie corse,
Whose wals were high, but nothing strong, nor thick,
And strong aduizement of six wisards old,
The Sarazin was stout, and wondrous strong,
Or breake the chayne of strong necessitee,
At them he gan to reare his bristles strong,
And mightie strong was turnd to feeble fraile.
And ouer-wrestled his strong enemie,
Whose hilts were burnisht gold, and handle strong
He forst to castle strong to take their flight,
Nigh to a castle builded strong and hie:
No gate so strong, no locke so firme and fast,
Which is through rage more strong then both were erst;
With cruell malice and strong tyranny:
And that weake captiue wight now wexed strong,
But all in vaine: no fort can be so strong,
Who then can striue with strong necessitie,
Was woxen strong, and left her fruitfull nest;
Whose wals and towres were builded high and strong
And with strong flight did forcibly diuide
Till struggling strong did him at last constraine,
For truth is strong, her rightfull cause to plead,
Too false and strong for earthly skill or might,
The strong it weakens with infirmitie,
The strong through pleasure soonest falles, the weake through smart.
And wondrous strong by nature, and by skilfull frame.
Through strong opinion of his matchlesse might:
Pursew the end of their strong enmity,
Weake she makes stro[n]g & stro[n]g thing does increace,
Weake she makes stro[n]g & stro[n]g thing does increace,
The strong extremities of their outrage;
But when strong passion, or weake fleshlinesse
Teach him the weake to strengthen, & the stro[n]g suppresse.
Then when she is withdrawen, or strong withstood,
Thereon an yron lock did fasten firme and strong.
In his strong armes he stiffely him embraste,
Strong warres they make, and cruell battry bend
One in bright armes embatteiled full strong,
Thereby thine armes seeme stro[n]g, but manhood fraile;
And thralled her in chaines with strong effort,
Tho gan that villein wex so fiers and strong,
So proudly pricketh on his courser strong,
Then she with liquors strong his eyes did steepe,
Yet with strong reason maistred passion fraile,
Weake hands, but counsell is most strong in age.
That houses forme within was rude and strong,
But huge great yron chests and coffers strong,
So stoutly he withstood their strong assay,
But when he stroke most strong, the dint deceiu'd,
With comely compasse, and compacture strong,
And the strong passion mard her modest grace,
Right firme & strong, though somewhat they declind;
Did head against them make, and strong munificence.
And built Cairleill, and built Cairleon strong.
And after all an army strong she leau'd,
Till that her sisters children, woxen strong
Restraining stealth, and strong extortion;
As that, which strong affections do apply
And lay strong siege about it far and wide.
In strong entrenchments he did closely place,
Did lay strong siege, and battailous assault,
With stings of carnall lust, and strong effort
That was most strong in most infirmitee;
With his stiffe oares did brush the sea so strong,
With a strong gard, all reskew to preuent,
That truth is strong, and trew loue most of might,
To loose her warlike limbs and strong effort,
Did easily beleeue her strong extremitie.
Strong warre vpon the Paynim brethren, hight
Why do thy cruell billowes beat so strong,
Through thy strong buffets and outrageous blowes,
She left, pursewing that same foster strong;
His shamefull head from his auengement strong.
In a strong rocky Caue, which is they say,
So strong is passion, that no reason heares.
And in strong banckes his violence enclose,
And meekely stoup vnto the victour strong:
Of his strong foe, lay tombled in the myre,
An armed knight, vpon a courser strong,
That all men feare to tempt his billowes strong,
In which the great Goemagot of strong
No fort so fensible, no wals so strong,
By strong enchauntments and blacke Magicke leare,
And through the roofe of her strong brasen towre
Of mighty Conquerours and Captaines strong,
Cald by strong charmes out of eternall night,
Then laid the noble Championesse strong hond
Great cities ransackt, and strong castles rast,
There also was the name of Nimrod strong,
With all their force, and battell strong to wage
Stout Priamond, but not so strong to strike,
Strong Diamond, but not so stout a knight,
But Triamond was stout and strong alike:
But Cambell still more strong and greater grew,
That we may vs reserue both fresh and strong,
But the more strong and stiffely that he ran,
All sixe strong groomes, but one then other more:
Like to a stubborne steede whom strong hand would restraine.
Yet he with strong perswasions her asswaged,
Whereat the Prince full wrath, his strong right hand
Ne was there man so strong, but he downe bore,
To yeeld strong succour to that gentle swayne,
Then gan they ransacke that same Castle strong,
Ne helmets bright, ne hawberks strong did spare,
And it was seated in an Island strong,
There reared was a castle faire and strong,
Which with so strong attempt I had begonne.
Mightie Chrysaor, and Caicus strong;
And shame on you, ï¿½ men, which boast your strong
Strong Allo tombling from Slewlogher steep,
Deliuer hence out of this dungeon strong,
And with strong hand their fruitfull rancknes did deface.
Whom a strong tyrant did vniustly thrall,
Did with strong hand withhold: Grantorto was his name.
And strong as Lyon in his Lordly might.
That keepes a Bridges passage by strong hond,
Through strong oppression of his powre extort;
By which he stil them holds, & keepes with strong effort.
For that he is so puissant and strong,
Ne euer Artegall his griple strong
And then the Gyant stroue with puissance strong
And there before them stood a Coffer strong,
Of strong compulsion, and streight violence,
Not by strong hand compelled thereunto,
But left his loue, albe her strong request,
With all their force to worke auengement strong
Is wondrous strong, and hewen farre vnder ground
With a strong yron chaine and coller bound,
Till strong constraint did her thereto enforce.
By a strong Tyrant, who inuaded has
Whereof she glad, now needing strong defence,
By her strong foe, who had defaced cleene
There eke he placed a strong garrisone,
That weakens her, and makes her party strong:
And forced them, how euer strong and stout
No faith so firme, no trust can be so strong,
Of colour rustie browne, but sure and strong;
Which with strong powre did them long time oppresse;
Hard by a streight there stands a castle strong,
Shall driue a Mill, within strong bancks is pent,
Who through stro[n]g powre had now her self in hould,
How euer strong and fortunate in fight,
Till of his wounds he wexed hole and strong,
But he me first, through pride and puissance strong
That through the mayles had made so strong a breach
He with strong hand down fro[m] his steed me throw'th,
But still his passion grew more violent and strong.
Since I was ten yeares old, now growen to stature strong.
And being now high time these strong ioynts to imploy.
Full on the breast him strooke, so strong and hard,
Now when as Calepine was woxen strong,
His steede now strong through rest so long a space,
The second not so strong but wise, Decetto;
The third nor strong nor wise, but spightfullest Defetto.
And sternely with strong hand it from his handling kept.
And the strong course of their displeasure breake,
But being growen strong, it forth doth bring
Is greatest shame: for oft it falles, that strong
That cursed caytiue, my strong enemy,
Albe the stroke so strong and puissant were,
In his strong hand their rugged teats to hold,
For he was strong and mightily stiffe pight,
Did striue to match with strong contention,
Amongst those theeues, which her in bondage strong
To marchants, but was sau'd with strong defence?
Vntill the damzell gan to wex more sound and strong.
And rage to quaile, he tooke a muzzell strong
Like as whylome that strong Tirynthian swaine,
To see him leade that Beast in bondage strong,
He growen is so great and strong of late,
Till ryper yeares he raught, and stronger stay:
That in the Realme ere long they stronger arre,
And raysd him vp much stronger then before,
Sith him he saw still stronger grow through strife,
Withouten perill of the stronger pride:
Yet was the younger stronger in his state
But Thame was stronger, and of better stay;
Like fiercely met. But Artegall was stronger,
Where still the stronger doth the weake deuoure,
With stronger death, and feared their decay,
That strongest Oake might seeme to ouerthrow.
Full strongly armd, and on a courser free,
And him so strongly stroke, that to the ground him feld.
And.strooke so strongly, that the knotty string
To ouerthrow him strongly did assay,
So strongly, that vneathes it can refraine
And of him catching hold him strongly stayd
In glistring steele, and strongly fortifide:
Yet oft the Briton kings against them strongly swayd.
And here arriuing, strongly challenged
Forward they passe, and strongly he them rowes,
But th'heedfull Boateman strongly forth did stretch
They tooke them both, & both them strongly bound
That for his trusty seruaunts doth so strongly fight.
Against it strongly striue, and yield thee not,
Strongly to aide his countrey, to withstand
Strongly the straunge knight ran, and sturdily
The same to loue he strongly was constraind:
She struggled strongly both with foot and hand,
Their steel-hed speares they strongly coucht, and met
Yet one of many was so strongly bent
Both strongly arm'd, as fearing one another;
Which mote the feebled Britons strongly flancke
And to him driuing strongly downe the tide,
With his great yron sledge doth strongly on it beat.
With which wise Nature did them strongly bynd,
To which the Lion strongly doth gainesay,
Nought vnder heauen so strongly doth allure
Together met, and strongly either strooke
She doth support, and strongly beateth downe
He gan that Ladie strongly to appele
Strongly did Zele her haynous fact enforce,
And her long taile and fethers strongly shooke,
Strongly he stroue out of her greedy gripe
Vppon her wide great wings, and strongly flew
And strongly wading through the waues vnused,
That doth thus strongly ward the Castle of the ford.
And strooke so strongly, that the Carle with paine
And strooke at her with more then manly force,
The Geaunt strooke so maynly mercilesse,
His force was vaine, and strooke more often wide,
With that he drew his flaming sword, and strooke
Sometimes a thwart, sometimes he strooke him strayt,
Strooke him so hugely, that through great constraint
With that he strooke, and th'other strooke withall,
With that he strooke, and th'other strooke withall,
And strooke, and foynd, and lasht outrageously,
And strooke at him so sternely, that he made
Againe through both the sides he strooke him quight,
That with her crooked keele the land she strooke,
Streight way he with his vertuous staffe them strooke,
Strooke her full on the brest, that made her downe
And strooke at him with force so violent,
Thereat was suddein strooke with great astonishment.
Her Steed did stagger with that puissaunt strooke;
And awfull terror deepe into him strooke,
Abiecting, th'earth with his faire forhead strooke:
Vnwares it strooke into her snowie chest,
Strooke him so hugely, that in swowne he lay,
So sorely he her strooke, that thence it glaunst
And therewithall at him right furiously she strooke.
So furiously she strooke in her first heat,
And with that word him strooke, that streight he did expire.
And at her strooke with puissance fearefull fell;
Vpon her helmet he againe her strooke,
Tho with her sword on him she flatling strooke,
Together met, and strongly either strooke
Thenceforth he car'd no more, which way he strooke,
And with his mortal steel quite throgh the body strooke.
Through all three bodies he him strooke attonce;
Three times, as in defiance, there he strooke;
Tho with her huge long taile she at him strooke,
He with his sword it strooke, that without faile
Right in the flanke him strooke with deadly dreare,
Which Artegall perceiuing, strooke no more,
And with his speare strooke me one stroke or twaine;
Strooke him, as seemeth, vnderneath the hart,
Strooke through his shoulder, that the blood ensew'd
Full on the breast him strooke, so strong and hard,
Him with his fist vnwares on th'head he strooke,
He stayd his second strooke, and did his hand abase.
And with his yron club to ground him strooke;
And strooke so strongly, that the Carle with paine
With which so sternely he the monster strooke,
Sternely he turnd againe, when he him strooke
That hand or foot to stirre he stroue in vaine:
And stroue to match, in royall rich array,
And stroue to maister sorrowfull assay,
And stroue for to amaze the weaker sights;
And whiles he stroue his combred clubbe to quight
Yet still he stroue to cloke his inward bale,
And stroue to loose the farre infixed sting:
For all his washing cleaner. Still he stroue,
And to his mistresse each himselfe stroue to aduaunce.
Still stroue their stubborne rages to reuoke,
Each stroue to please, and others pleasure to fulfill.
And euery of them stroue, with most delights,
And stroue in vaine, the one himselfe to drowne,
And eke her louer stroue: but all in vaine;
And the moist daughters of huge Atlas stroue
Long while he stroue in his courageous brest,
That seemed those two vertues stroue to find
The silly virgin stroue him to withstand,
It fortuned, whilest thus she stifly stroue,
With busie care they stroue him to awake,
That stroue in vaine him long to haue withstood,
So cruelly these Knights stroue for that Ladies sake.
There they together stroue and struggled long,
And then the Gyant stroue with puissance strong
But rather stroue extremities to way,
In which all stroue with perill to winne fame.
Together stroue, and kindled wrathfull fires:
And still the more she stroue it to subdew,
Strongly he stroue out of her greedy gripe
Long while he tug'd and stroue, to get it out,
Whilest they together for the quarrey stroue,
Stroue to appease him, and perswaded long:
For still the more he stroue, the more the Knight
And strow with flowres the lamentable beare:
And spoiles, wherewith he all the ground did strow,
So did the Championesse those two there strow,
The holy fire, and all the embers strow
They trode, and on the ground their liues did strow,
He strowd an Aue-Mary after and before.
And all the ground was strow'd with flowres, as fresh as May.
But scattred all about, and strow'd vpon the greene.
He saw the ground all strow'd, and that same Knight
Till he had strowd with bodies all the way;
Of murdred men which therein strowed lay,
And sacred ashes ouer it was strowed new.
And strowed round about, and by his side
Strowed with pleasauns, whose faire grassy ground
By shiuered speares, and swords all vnder strowen,
And with their garments strowes the paued street:
And with greene braunches strowing all the ground,
And in another corner wide were strowne
And saw the fieldes of faire Scamander strowne
Which when in vaine he tryde with struggeling.
She struggled strongly both with foot and hand,
There they together stroue and struggled long,
At last when long she struggled had in vaine,
Till struggling strong did him at last constraine,
Whiles thus they strugled in that idle waue,
His strugling soule, and swelling throbs empeach
Ouer his horses taile aboue a stryde:
With easie steps so soft as foot could stryde.
And stalking stately like a Crane, did stryde
Then brought he forth Sedition, breeding stryfe
And stryfull Atin in their stubborne mynd
That stryfull hag with gealous discontent
He stearnly shooke, and therewith fierce did stryke
And euery one to runne the swiftest stryu'd;
Stryuing long time in vaine it to withstond;
Stryuing in vaine that nigh his bowels brast,
Doe fall together, stryuing each to get
For their bad Stuard neither plough'd nor sowed,
With which the stubborn feends he to his seruice bound.
He that the stubborne Sprites can wisely tame,
He roar'd aloud, whiles life forsooke his stubborne brest.
Vnlesse she chaunst their stubborne mouths to twitch;
Stout Scipio, and stubborne Hanniball,
Her to perswade, that stubborne fort to yilde:
Such ioy he had, their stubborne harts to quell,
His stubborne steed with curbed canon bit,
Such percing griefe her stubborne hart did wound,
And with streight diet tame his stubborne malady.
Still stroue their stubborne rages to reuoke,
Through wounds, & strokes, & stubborne handeling,
Then stubborne perturbation, to the same;
And stryfull Atin in their stubborne mynd
And with sweet science mollifide their stubborne harts.
Your stubborne hart t'affect with fraile infirmity.
Eftsoones their stubborne courages were queld,
His stubborne brest gan secret pleasaunce to embrace.
Dare not aduenture on the stubborne pray,
My stubborne smart, but more annoyance breed,
To mitigate his stubborne mallady:
So thinking for to make her stubborne courage quaile.
Vpon whose stubborne neck, whereat he raues
And bad the stubborne flames to yield him way:
Like to a stubborne steede whom strong hand would restraine.
The next, the stubborne Newre, whose waters gray
His stubborne heart, that neuer felt misfare
Dame Venus sonne that tameth stubborne youth
The stubborne mettall seeketh to subdew,
Through stubborne handling of her loue-sicke hart;
Vppon two stubborne oakes, which stand so neare,
Her stubborne hart with inward deepe effect,
To rule the stubborne rage of passion blinde:
Through such her stubborne stifnesse, and hard hart,
Euen for stubborne pride, which her restrayned.
Her stubborne hart, which loue before disdayned,
By strength haue ouerthrowne a stubborne steare,
And all about old stockes and stubs of trees,
Yet stuck, with carkasses exanimate
The steely head stucke fast still in his flesh,
Where fast it stucke, ne would there out be got:
Whose steale was yron studded, but not long,
For all her studie was and all her thought,
His studie was true Iustice how to deale,
Perforce their studies broke, and them besought
Abroad in armes, at home in studious kind
He to his study goes, and there amiddes
Made of straunge stuffe, but all to worne and ragged,
Stuft with steele-headed darts, wherewith she queld
For she was stuft with rancour and despight
To stumble, that his rider nigh he cast;
Fiue ioynts thereof he hewd, and but the stump him left.
Which stunck so vildly, that it forst him slacke
That through the great contagion direfull deadly stunck.
Wherewith he was so stund, that he n'ote ryde,
With great amazement they were stupefide;
In stupid sorow, sith thy iuster merit
He was to weete a stout and sturdie thiefe,
And sturdie courage tame with dreadfull aw,
With sturdie steps came stalking in his sight,
Therewith his sturdie courage soone was quayd,
But gan his sturdie sterne about to weld,
Ne ought his sturdie strokes might stand afore,
The walles so stoutly with their sturdie maine,
Strongly the straunge knight ran, and sturdily
Him first saluted with a sturdy stroke;
A sturdy villein, striding stiffe and bold,
As when a sturdy ploughman with his hynde
And Sture, that parteth with his pleasant floods
The Cle, the Were, the Grant, the Sture, the Rowne.
That with their sturre they troubled all the traine;
That was Ambition, rash desire to sty,
Thought with his wings to stye aboue the ground;
Salue to your sore, yet loue can higher stye,
From wandring Stygian shores, where it doth endlesse moue.
Doest thou sit wayling by black Stygian lake,
Which she in Stygian lake, ay burning bright,
If euer he transgrest the fatall Stygian lawes.
With which he wonts the Stygian realmes inuade,
Which long hath waited by the Stygian strond.
Doth praise thee oft, and oft from Stygian deepe
By Stygian lake I vow, whose sad annoy
Of Stygian Gods, which doe her loue enuy;
From Stygian shores, where late it wandered;
As one in feare the Stygian gods t'offend,
His soule descended downe into the Stygian reame.
His Leman from the Stygian Princes boure.
More loathd then Lerna, or then Stygian lake,
Where he was fostred long in Stygian fen,
And long in darksome Stygian den vpbrought,
How euer gay and goodly be the style,
An huge great paire of bellowes, which did styre
Vnable to arise, or foot or hand to styre.
At which Cocytus quakes, and Styx is put to flight.
Of hellish Styx, which hidden vertue to it gaue.
In which old Styx her aged bones alway,
Old Styx the Grandame of the Gods, doth lay.
Till morrow next, that I the Elfe subdew,
Did breed him endlesse labour to subdew:
And when him list the prouder lookes subdew,
Haue enterprizd that Monster to subdew;
Those creeping flames by reason to subdew,
Who well could menage and subdew his pride,
So hasty heat soone cooled to subdew:
Mote stead you much your purpose to subdew.
Those germans did subdew all Germany,
Whilest Romanes dayly did the weake subdew:
So made them victours, whom he did subdew.
And to them selues all Nations did subdew:
All monsters to subdew to him, that did it beare.
With which he godly Oswald shall subdew,
Yet shall a third both these, and thine subdew;
Which darknesse shall subdew, and heauen win;
With reason dew the passion to subdew,
Subdew, through conquest of your wondrous might,
With harder meanes he cast her to subdew,
And strife, and warre, and anger does subdew:
The stubborne mettall seeketh to subdew,
And still the more she stroue it to subdew,
That shortly did all other beasts subdew.
In bloud of Kings, and great hoastes to subdew?
But the two knights themselues their captains did subdew.
Till I him ouertake, or else subdew:
Who hath not learnd him selfe first to subdew:
subdew, and bynd in bands.
Did him suppresse, and forcibly subdew;
Her chast hart had subdewd, to learne Dame pleasures toy.
But fairely tempring fond desire subdewd,
I liue this day, and see my foes subdewd,
Thus Brute this Realme vnto his rule subdewd,
He Easterland subdewd, and Danmarke wonne,
Ireland subdewd, and therein fixt his throne,
He had subdew'd and them his vassals made,
Subdewd with losse of many Britons bold:
And is subdewd by guile:
For his huge club, which had subdew'd of old
